  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "At the Canterbury Stone Circle in November, Miranda is accompanied by a man who discusses the necessity of sacrifice to create beauty. He leads her to a stone carved with a double axe and offers her a golden goblet filled with peach-flavored liquid, telling her to drink so she will always be happy. As Miranda prepares to drink, Nicholas Lanser intervenes, pulling her away from the man and a knife. Lanser informs Miranda that there is no sacrifice ceremony and reveals that a missing exchange student was actually found dead in a well. He identifies the man who brought Miranda to the circle as the person responsible for the girl's death.\n\nIn a subsequent meeting involving Poirot, the Chief Constable, and other officials, Miranda is questioned about what she witnessed nearly two years prior. She explains that she previously saw a man and a woman carrying a body in the quarry garden. At the time, she saw blood on a scarf and a knife, but she initially believed it was an accident. She later witnessed the same pair in March, shortly after Easter, discussing a Greek island and a signed agreement. Miranda identifies the two individuals as Mrs. Dreker and Michael. She admits she did not report the incident because Michael had convinced her that the act was a necessary ritual sacrifice.",
